5. Platform Independent
Definition

Java follows the principle:

Write Once, Run Anywhere (WORA)

You write the program once and run it on any operating system that has a JVM.

Process
Java Source Code
        ↓
Java Compiler
        ↓
Bytecode (.class)
        ↓
JVM
        ↓
Machine Code
        ↓
Output
Example

A Java program created on Windows can also run on Linux or macOS without changing the source code.

6. Portable
Definition

Java programs can easily move from one system to another.

No need to rewrite the code for different operating systems.

Example

A banking application written in Java can run on Windows, Linux, and macOS.

7. Secure
Definition

Java provides strong security because it:

Does not use pointer arithmetic
Has a bytecode verifier
Runs programs inside the JVM
Provides automatic memory management
Example

Java applications used in banking and enterprise software benefit from these security features.

8. Robust
Definition

Robust means strong and reliable.

Java reduces crashes through:

Exception Handling
Garbage Collection
Strong memory management
Type checking
Example
public class Demo {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        try {

            int a = 10 / 0;

        }

        catch(Exception e) {

            System.out.println("Exception Handled");

        }

    }

}
Output
Exception Handled
9. Architecture Neutral
Definition

Java bytecode is not dependent on processor architecture.

It can run on different CPU architectures using the JVM.

Examples:

Intel
AMD
ARM
10. Interpreted
Definition

Java compiler converts source code into bytecode.

The JVM interprets and executes the bytecode.

Process
.java
   ↓

Compiler

   ↓

.class

   ↓

JVM

   ↓

Machine Code
11. High Performance
Definition

Java is faster than many interpreted languages because of the Just-In-Time (JIT) Compiler.

The JIT compiler converts bytecode into native machine code during execution.

Example

Java applications are widely used in enterprise systems that require good performance.

12. Multithreaded
Definition

Java supports running multiple tasks simultaneously using threads.

Example

One application can:

Download files
Play music
Update the screen

all at the same time.

