            JAVA NOTES - JDK, JRE AND JVM
=========================================================

Topic No: 3

---------------------------------------------------------
1. Introduction
---------------------------------------------------------

Whenever we write a Java program, three important components
work together:

1. JDK (Java Development Kit)
2. JRE (Java Runtime Environment)
3. JVM (Java Virtual Machine)

Every Java programmer should understand these three terms
because they are among the most frequently asked interview
questions.

---------------------------------------------------------
2. What is JDK?
---------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

JDK (Java Development Kit) is a complete software package
used for developing Java applications.

It contains everything required to write, compile, debug,
and execute Java programs.

In simple words:

"JDK is used by Java Developers."

Formula:

JDK = JRE + Development Tools

---------------------------------------------------------
3. Components of JDK
---------------------------------------------------------

The JDK contains:

• JRE (Java Runtime Environment)
• JVM (Java Virtual Machine)
• Java Compiler (javac)
• Java Debugger
• Java Documentation Tool (javadoc)
• Jar Tool
• Java Development Utilities

---------------------------------------------------------
4. JDK Diagram
---------------------------------------------------------

                    JDK
      --------------------------------
      |                              |
 Development Tools                 JRE
 (javac, javadoc, jar)              |
                                   JVM

---------------------------------------------------------
5. Uses of JDK
---------------------------------------------------------

• Write Java programs
• Compile Java programs
• Debug Java programs
• Create Jar files
• Generate documentation
• Run Java applications

---------------------------------------------------------
6. Example
---------------------------------------------------------

Suppose you write:

Hello.java

To compile:

javac Hello.java

Compiler creates:

Hello.class

The JDK provides the "javac" compiler.

---------------------------------------------------------
7. What is JRE?
---------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

JRE (Java Runtime Environment) provides everything required
to run Java applications.

It does NOT contain development tools like javac.

In simple words:

"JRE is used for running Java programs."

Formula:

JRE = JVM + Java Libraries

---------------------------------------------------------
8. Components of JRE
---------------------------------------------------------

• JVM
• Core Java Libraries
• Supporting Files
• Runtime Environment

---------------------------------------------------------
9. JRE Diagram
---------------------------------------------------------

              JRE
      ------------------
      |                |
 Java Libraries      JVM

---------------------------------------------------------
10. Uses of JRE
---------------------------------------------------------

• Runs Java applications
• Provides Java libraries
• Loads Java classes
• Supports JVM execution

---------------------------------------------------------
11. Example
---------------------------------------------------------

If your friend wants to run your Java software but does not
want to develop Java applications, only JRE is enough.

---------------------------------------------------------
12. What is JVM?
---------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

JVM (Java Virtual Machine) is an abstract machine that
executes Java bytecode.

It converts bytecode into machine code.

It is responsible for making Java platform independent.

---------------------------------------------------------
13. Uses of JVM
---------------------------------------------------------

• Loads class files
• Verifies bytecode
• Executes bytecode
• Converts bytecode to machine code
• Memory management
• Garbage collection
• Exception handling

---------------------------------------------------------
14. JVM Working
---------------------------------------------------------

Java Source Code
       |

Hello.java
       |

Compiler (javac)
       |

Hello.class (Bytecode)
       |

JVM
       |

Machine Code
       |

Output

---------------------------------------------------------
15. Real-Life Example
---------------------------------------------------------

Suppose you have a PDF file.

The PDF file can be opened on Windows, Linux, and Mac if
they have a PDF Reader.

Similarly,

Java Bytecode (.class) can run on Windows, Linux, or Mac
if they have JVM installed.

---------------------------------------------------------
16. Why Java is Platform Independent?
---------------------------------------------------------

Java source code is compiled into Bytecode.

Bytecode is NOT operating system dependent.

JVM converts bytecode into machine code according to the
operating system.

Therefore:

Write Once
Run Anywhere (WORA)

---------------------------------------------------------
