--------------------------------------------------------------
5. Package Declaration
--------------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

A package is used to organize Java classes into folders.

Syntax:

package packageName;

Example:

package com.company;

Meaning:

The class belongs to the package named "com.company".

Advantages:

• Better organization
• Avoids duplicate class names
• Easy project management

Note:

Package declaration should always be the first statement
in a Java file.

--------------------------------------------------------------
6. Import Statement
--------------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

The import statement is used to use predefined classes
from Java packages.

Syntax:

import packageName.ClassName;

Example:

import java.util.Scanner;

Now Scanner class can be used in the program.

Example:

import java.util.*;

This imports all classes inside java.util package.

--------------------------------------------------------------
7. Class Declaration
--------------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

A class is a blueprint for creating objects.

Syntax:

public class ClassName {

}

Example:

public class Student {

}

Rules:

• Class name should start with uppercase.
• File name should match class name.
• Only one public class per file.

Example:

File Name:

Student.java

Class Name:

public class Student

Both must be the same.

--------------------------------------------------------------
8. Main Method
--------------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

The main() method is the starting point of every Java
application.

Execution begins from main().

Syntax:

public static void main(String[] args)

{

}

--------------------------------------------------------------
