==============================================================
            JAVA NOTES - EXCEPTION HANDLING
==============================================================

TOPIC NO: 13

==============================================================
1. INTRODUCTION
==============================================================

In Java, errors can occur during program execution.

These errors are called EXCEPTIONS.

If not handled properly, program will terminate abruptly.

Example:
- Divide by zero
- File not found
- Array index out of bounds
- Null pointer access

To handle such situations, Java provides:
→ Exception Handling

==============================================================
2. DEFINITION
==============================================================

Exception handling is a mechanism in Java used to handle
runtime errors so that normal flow of program continues.

==============================================================
3. TYPES OF ERRORS
==============================================================

1. Compile-time error
2. Runtime error (Exception)
3. Logical error

--------------------------------------------------------------
Compile-time error:
- Syntax mistakes
- Detected by compiler

Runtime error:
- Occurs during execution
- Handled using exceptions

Logical error:
- Program runs but output is wrong

==============================================================
4. EXCEPTION HIERARCHY
==============================================================

Object
  |
Throwable
  |
-------------------------
|                       |
Exception            Error
|
RuntimeException

==============================================================
5. TYPES OF EXCEPTIONS
==============================================================

A. Checked Exception (Compile-time)
B. Unchecked Exception (Runtime)

--------------------------------------------------------------
Checked Exception:
Handled at compile time

Example:
IOException, SQLException

--------------------------------------------------------------
Unchecked Exception:
Occurs at runtime

Example:
ArithmeticException
NullPointerException
ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException

==============================================================
6. TRY-CATCH BLOCK
==============================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------
Definition:
--------------------------------------------------------------
try block contains risky code
catch block handles exception

--------------------------------------------------------------
Syntax:
--------------------------------------------------------------
try {
    // risky code
}
catch(Exception e) {
    // handling code
}

==============================================================
7. EXAMPLE (DIVIDE BY ZERO)
==============================================================
```java id="try1"
public class Demo {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        try {
            int a = 10;
            int b = 0;

            int c = a / b;

            System.out.println(c);
        }
        catch(ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero");
        }

        System.out.println("Program continues...");
    }
}
````

Output:
Cannot divide by zero
Program continues...

==============================================================
8. FINALLY BLOCK
================

---

## Definition:

finally block always executes whether exception occurs or not.

==============================================================
Example:
========

```java id="fin1"
try {
    int a = 10 / 0;
}
catch(Exception e) {
    System.out.println("Error occurred");
}
finally {
    System.out.println("Finally block executed");
}
```

Output:
Error occurred
Finally block executed

==============================================================
9. MULTIPLE CATCH BLOCK
=======================

```java id="mc1"
try {
    int arr[] = new int[3];
    arr[5] = 10;
}
catch(ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Arithmetic error");
}
catch(ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
    System.out.println("Array error");
}
```

==============================================================
10. THROW KEYWORD
=================

---

## Definition:

throw is used to explicitly throw an exception.

==============================================================
Example:
========

```java id="thr1"
public class Demo {

    static void checkAge(int age) {
        if(age < 18) {
            throw new ArithmeticException("Not eligible");
        }
        else {
            System.out.println("Eligible");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        checkAge(15);
    }
}
```

==============================================================
11. THROWS KEYWORD
==================

---

## Definition:

throws is used to declare exceptions in method signature.

==============================================================
Example:
========

```java id="thr2"
import java.io.*;

public class Demo {

    static void readFile() throws IOException {
        throw new IOException("File error");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            readFile();
        }
        catch(IOException e) {
            System.out.println(e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

==============================================================
12. COMMON EXCEPTIONS
=====================

1. ArithmeticException → divide by zero
2. NullPointerException → null object access
3. ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException → invalid index
4. NumberFormatException → invalid conversion
5. IOException → file handling issue

==============================================================
13. NULL POINTER EXAMPLE
========================

```java id="np1"
String s = null;

System.out.println(s.length());
```

Result:
NullPointerException

==============================================================
14. REAL LIFE EXAMPLE
=====================

ATM System:

* Enter wrong PIN → exception
* Insufficient balance → exception
* System error → handled safely

==============================================================
15. ADVANTAGES
==============

✔ Prevents program crash
✔ Improves reliability
✔ Better user experience
✔ Easy debugging

==============================================================
16. DISADVANTAGES
=================

✘ Increases code length
✘ Slight performance overhead

==============================================================
17. COMMON MISTAKES
===================

❌ Empty catch block

catch(Exception e) { }

❌ Not handling runtime errors

❌ Using general Exception everywhere

==============================================================
18. INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=======================

Q1. What is exception?
→ Runtime error that disrupts program flow.

Q2. Difference between error and exception?
→ Error = system level
→ Exception = program level

Q3. What is try-catch?
→ Used to handle exceptions.

Q4. What is finally block?
→ Always executes.

