````text id="mt1d8k"
==============================================================
            JAVA NOTES - MULTITHREADING IN JAVA
==============================================================

TOPIC NO: 15

==============================================================
1. INTRODUCTION
==============================================================

In Java, programs normally execute step by step (single thread).

But in real applications, multiple tasks run at the same time.

Example:
- Music playing + downloading file
- Bank server handling multiple users
- Games running animations + logic

This is done using MULTITHREADING.

==============================================================
2. DEFINITION
==============================================================

Multithreading is a process of executing multiple threads
simultaneously within a single program.

==============================================================
3. WHAT IS THREAD
==============================================================

A thread is a lightweight subprocess.

It is the smallest unit of execution in Java.

==============================================================
4. SINGLE THREAD VS MULTI THREAD
==============================================================

SINGLE THREAD:
- One task at a time
- Slower execution

MULTI THREAD:
- Multiple tasks at same time
- Faster execution

==============================================================
5. ADVANTAGES OF MULTITHREADING
==============================================================

✔ Better CPU utilization
✔ Faster execution
✔ Efficient resource sharing
✔ Smooth performance

==============================================================
6. THREAD LIFE CYCLE
==============================================================

1. New
2. Runnable
3. Running
4. Waiting/Blocked
5. Terminated

--------------------------------------------------------------
FLOW:
--------------------------------------------------------------
New → Runnable → Running → Terminated

==============================================================
7. CREATING THREAD IN JAVA
==============================================================

Two ways:

1. Extending Thread class
2. Implementing Runnable interface

==============================================================
8. METHOD 1: EXTENDING THREAD CLASS
==============================================================
```java id="th1"
class MyThread extends Thread {

    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is running");
    }
}

public class Demo {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        MyThread t1 = new MyThread();

        t1.start();
    }
}
````

OUTPUT:
Thread is running

==============================================================
IMPORTANT:
==========

✔ run() → defines task
✔ start() → starts thread execution

DO NOT call run() directly.

==============================================================
9. METHOD 2: IMPLEMENTING RUNNABLE
==================================

```java id="th2"
class MyRunnable implements Runnable {

    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Runnable thread running");
    }
}

public class Demo {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Thread t1 = new Thread(new MyRunnable());

        t1.start();
    }
}
```

==============================================================
10. THREAD METHODS
==================

✔ start() → starts thread
✔ run() → task
✔ sleep(ms) → pause thread
✔ join() → wait for thread
✔ getName() → thread name
✔ setName() → set thread name

==============================================================
11. SLEEP METHOD
================

```java id="th3"
public class Demo {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.println(i);
            Thread.sleep(1000);
        }
    }
}
```

==============================================================
12. SYNCHRONIZATION
===================

---

## Definition:

Synchronization is used to control access of multiple threads
to a shared resource.

It prevents data inconsistency.

==============================================================
13. SYNCHRONIZED METHOD EXAMPLE
===============================

```java id="th4"
class Bank {

    synchronized void withdraw(int amount) {

        System.out.println("Processing withdrawal: " + amount);

        try {
            Thread.sleep(1000);
        } catch(Exception e) {}

        System.out.println("Withdrawal completed");
    }
}
```

==============================================================
14. THREAD PROBLEM WITHOUT SYNCHRONIZATION
==========================================

✔ Race condition
✔ Data inconsistency
✔ Wrong output

==============================================================
15. REAL LIFE EXAMPLE
=====================

Bank System:

* Multiple users withdrawing money at same time
* Synchronization ensures correct balance

==============================================================
16. THREAD PRIORITY
===================

Priority range:
1 to 10

* 1 → MIN_PRIORITY
* 5 → NORM_PRIORITY
* 10 → MAX_PRIORITY

==============================================================
17. COMMON MISTAKES
===================

❌ Calling run() instead of start()

❌ Not handling sleep exception

❌ Forgetting thread synchronization

==============================================================
18. INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=======================

Q1. What is thread?
→ Smallest unit of execution.

Q2. What is multithreading?
→ Multiple threads executing simultaneously.

Q3. Difference between run() and start()?
→ start() creates new thread, run() does not.

Q4. What is synchronization?
→ Controlling access to shared resources.

Q5. Why use multithreading?
→ Better performance and CPU utilization.

==============================================================
19. PRACTICE QUESTIONS
======================

1. Create thread using Thread class
2. Create thread using Runnable
3. Print numbers using thread
4. Demonstrate sleep method
5. Demonstrate synchronization
6. Create bank withdrawal system
7. Print thread names
8. Simulate multiple users login

==============================================================
20. QUICK REVISION
==================

✔ Thread = smallest execution unit
✔ Multithreading = multiple threads running
✔ start() = start thread
✔ run() = task method
✔ synchronization = safe resource access

==============================================================
END OF TOPIC
==========================================================================
