6. TIME COMPLEXITY
==============================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------
Definition:
--------------------------------------------------------------
Time Complexity tells how execution time increases
with input size.

==============================================================
7. BIG O NOTATION
==============================================================

Big-O represents worst case performance.

COMMON COMPLEXITIES:

✔ O(1)   → Constant time
✔ O(log n) → Logarithmic
✔ O(n)   → Linear
✔ O(n log n) → Good sorting
✔ O(n²)  → Nested loops (slow)
✔ O(2ⁿ)  → Very slow (recursion)

==============================================================
8. EXAMPLES OF TIME COMPLEXITY
==============================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------
O(1) Example:
--------------------------------------------------------------
```java
int a = 10;
System.out.println(a);
````

---

## O(n) Example:

```java
for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
}
```

---

## O(n²) Example:

```java
for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    for(int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
        System.out.println(i + " " + j);
    }
}
```

==============================================================
9. SPACE COMPLEXITY
===================

---

## Definition:

Space Complexity measures memory usage of a program.

Example:

* Using arrays → more space
* Using variables → less space

==============================================================
10. ARRAY BASICS (DSA VIEW)
===========================

Array operations:
✔ Traversal
✔ Searching
✔ Sorting

Example:
Linear Search → O(n)

==============================================================
11. LINEAR SEARCH
=================

```java id="dsa1"
int arr[] = {10, 20, 30, 40};
int key = 30;

for(int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if(arr[i] == key) {
        System.out.println("Found at index " + i);
    }
}
```

Time Complexity: O(n)

==============================================================
12. BINARY SEARCH
=================

Works only on sorted array.

Time Complexity: O(log n)

==============================================================
13. BINARY SEARCH EXAMPLE
=========================

```java id="dsa2"
int arr[] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
int key = 30;

int low = 0;
int high = arr.length - 1;

while(low <= high) {

    int mid = (low + high) / 2;

    if(arr[mid] == key) {
        System.out.println("Found at " + mid);
        break;
    }
    else if(arr[mid] < key) {
        low = mid + 1;
    }
    else {
        high = mid - 1;
    }
}
```

==============================================================
14. SORTING BASICS
==================

Common sorting algorithms:
✔ Bubble Sort
✔ Selection Sort
✔ Insertion Sort
✔ Merge Sort (important)
✔ Quick Sort (important)

==============================================================
15. BUBBLE SORT EXAMPLE
=======================

```java id="dsa3"
int arr[] = {5, 3, 2, 4, 1};

for(int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    for(int j = 0; j < arr.length - 1; j++) {

        if(arr[j] > arr[j+1]) {
            int temp = arr[j];
            arr[j] = arr[j+1];
            arr[j+1] = temp;
        }
    }
}
```

Time Complexity: O(n²)

==============================================================
16. RECURSION INTRO
===================

Definition:
A function that calls itself is recursion.

Example:
Factorial, Fibonacci

==============================================================
17. FACTORIAL USING RECURSION
=============================

```java id="dsa4"
static int fact(int n) {

    if(n == 0) {
        return 1;
    }

    return n * fact(n - 1);
}
```

